{"TopicId":157080,"ForumId":29,"TopicTitle":"How to identify the Sun when it\u0026#039;s been renamed?","CreatedByName":"linuxgurugamer","CreatedById":129964,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-27T23:16:39Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"linuxgurugamer","CreatedById":129964,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-27T23:16:39Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSome planet packs rename the sun (Galilio\u0027s among others). \u00A0How can I identify which CelestialBody is the sun?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThanks\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Thomas P.","CreatedById":113164,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-27T23:23:31Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nDepends. If someone moves the stock sun to orbit another body (like the galactic core from GN), do you want to get the sun Kerbin is orbiting, or the *true* central body of the system?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"wasml","CreatedById":120438,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-28T02:30:41Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBit of a hack but I found (in limited testing) that crawling up the parent body chain until I found a body with a temp over some limit (think I used 2000) seemed to work. Not sure how low some of the extreme low mass stars can go, or how high a hot Jupiter can go, but 2K should be near the lower limit for a star. This of course assumes the mod star has a realistic temperature.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"sarbian","CreatedById":57146,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-28T12:50:59Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOr\u00A0Planetarium.fetch.Sun\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"linuxgurugamer","CreatedById":129964,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-02-28T12:55:54Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222970589\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022157080\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221488286259\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002257146\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022sarbian\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n4 minutes ago, sarbian said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOr\u00A0Planetarium.fetch.Sun\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat will work, thank you!!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"HebaruSan","CreatedById":156657,"CreatedDateTime":"2017-03-08T00:07:18Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThat\u0027s the best way if you\u00A0need to find it starting from scratch.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIf you already have a reference to a CelestialBody and need to determine\u00A0whether it\u0027s the Sun, I found that the Sun is the only body that is\u00A0its own referenceBody (I would have preferred null, but oh well).\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cpre class=\u0022ipsCode prettyprint prettyprinted\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E\u00A0 \u00A0 \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Ebool\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E isSun\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E(\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003ECelestialBody\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E body\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E)\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E{\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022kwd\u0022\u003Ereturn\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E(\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003Ebody\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E.\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan\u003EGetOrbit\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E().\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003EreferenceBody \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E==\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E body\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E);\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pln\u0022\u003E \u003C/span\u003E\u003Cspan class=\u0022pun\u0022\u003E}\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/pre\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}